In a press conference, Vice President Kamala Harris addressed the tragic shooting in Indianapolis and expressed condolences to the families affected. She emphasized the need to end gun violence in the country. Harris then welcomed the Prime Minister of Japan, Yoshihide Suga, who is the first world leader to visit the United States since the Biden administration took office. They discussed collaboration and friendship between the two countries, particularly regarding the Indo-Pacific region. Harris also mentioned her personal connection to the Japanese American community in California. Prime Minister Suga expressed gratitude for the invitation and praised the importance of the Japan-U.S. alliance, which is based on shared values of freedom, democracy, and the rule of law. Both leaders expressed eagerness to discuss various challenges and strengthen their alliance. The press conference concluded with Vice President Harris expressing her anticipation for the upcoming conversation.